              <h2>Polygon interior angles – definitions</h2>
              <p>
                A <strong>polygon</strong> is a 2D shape made from straight line
                segments joined end to end. At each vertex (corner) there is an
                <strong>interior angle</strong> inside the polygon and an
                <strong>exterior angle</strong> outside the polygon.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interior angle</strong>: the angle formed inside the
                  polygon at a vertex.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Exterior angle</strong>: the angle formed by extending
                  one side of the polygon at a vertex.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Regular polygon</strong>: all sides and all interior
                  angles are equal.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Formulas for interior and exterior angles</h2>

              <h3>1. Sum of interior angles</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>\[ S = (n - 2)\times 180^\circ \]</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(S\) = sum of interior angles</li>
                  <li>\(n\) = number of sides (and vertices)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                This works for any simple polygon (convex or concave) with \(n
                \ge 3\). You can think of it as splitting the polygon into \((n
                - 2)\) triangles, each with 180°.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Each interior angle of a regular polygon</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong> (regular polygon only)</p>
                <p>\[ A_{\text{int}} = \frac{(n - 2)\times 180^\circ}{n} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Because all interior angles are equal in a regular polygon, you
                just divide the total interior angle sum by the number of sides.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Each exterior angle of a regular polygon</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formulas</strong> (regular polygon)</p>
                <p>\[ A_{\text{ext}} = 180^\circ - A_{\text{int}} \]</p>
                <p>or equivalently</p>
                <p>\[ A_{\text{ext}} = \frac{360^\circ}{n} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For any convex polygon, the sum of one exterior angle at each
                vertex is always 360°. In a regular polygon, all exterior angles
                are equal, so each one is \(360^\circ / n\).
              </p>

              <h2>Step-by-step examples</h2>

              <h3>Example 1 – Sum of interior angles of a hexagon</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Question:</strong> What is the sum of the interior
                angles of a hexagon?
              </p>
              <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
              <ol>
                <li>A hexagon has \(n = 6\) sides.</li>
                <li>Use the formula \(S = (n - 2)\times 180^\circ\).</li>
                <li>
                  \(S = (6 - 2)\times 180^\circ = 4\times 180^\circ =
                  720^\circ\).
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                <strong>Answer:</strong> The sum of the interior angles of a
                hexagon is 720°.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Each interior angle of a regular octagon</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Question:</strong> Find each interior angle of a regular
                octagon.
              </p>
              <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
              <ol>
                <li>An octagon has \(n = 8\) sides.</li>
                <li>
                  First find the sum: \(S = (8 - 2)\times 180^\circ = 6\times
                  180^\circ = 1080^\circ\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Divide by \(n\): \(A_{\text{int}} = 1080^\circ / 8 =
                  135^\circ\).
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                <strong>Answer:</strong> Each interior angle of a regular
                octagon is 135°.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Example 3 – Find the number of sides from an interior angle
              </h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Question:</strong> A regular polygon has interior angles
                of 150°. How many sides does it have?
              </p>
              <p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
              <ol>
                <li>Let \(A_{\text{int}} = 150^\circ\).</li>
                <li>
                  Use the relationship between interior and exterior angles: \[
                  A_{\text{ext}} = 180^\circ - A_{\text{int}} = 180^\circ -
                  150^\circ = 30^\circ \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  For a regular polygon, \(A_{\text{ext}} = 360^\circ / n\), so:
                  \[ 30^\circ = \frac{360^\circ}{n} \Rightarrow n =
                  \frac{360^\circ}{30^\circ} = 12 \]
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                <strong>Answer:</strong> It is a regular 12-sided polygon (a
                dodecagon).
              </p>

              <h2>Interior vs exterior angles – key facts</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The sum of interior angles of an n-gon is \((n - 2)\times
                  180^\circ\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  The sum of one exterior angle at each vertex of a convex
                  polygon is always 360°.
                </li>
                <li>
                  In a regular polygon, interior and exterior angles at a vertex
                  form a straight line: \[ A_{\text{int}} + A_{\text{ext}} =
                  180^\circ \]
                </li>
                <li>
                  Concave polygons have at least one interior angle greater than
                  180°, but the same sum formula still applies.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>
                What is the formula for the sum of interior angles of a polygon?
              </h3>
              <p>
                For any simple polygon with \(n\) sides, the sum of the interior
                angles is \((n - 2)\times 180^\circ\). This comes from dividing
                the polygon into \((n - 2)\) triangles from one vertex.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I find each interior angle of a regular polygon?</h3>
              <p>
                First compute the sum of interior angles using \((n - 2)\times
                180^\circ\), then divide by \(n\): \[ A_{\text{int}} = \frac{(n
                - 2)\times 180^\circ}{n} \]
              </p>

              <h3>Can a polygon have interior angles greater than 180°?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. If a polygon is <strong>concave</strong>, at least one
                interior angle is greater than 180°. The formula for the sum of
                interior angles still holds as long as the polygon is simple
                (its sides do not cross).
              </p>

              <h3>
                How do I know if a regular polygon is possible from a given
                interior angle?
              </h3>
              <p>
                If you know each interior angle \(A_{\text{int}}\), compute \[ n
                = \frac{360^\circ}{180^\circ - A_{\text{int}}}. \] If \(n\) is a
                whole number ≥ 3, then a regular polygon with that interior
                angle exists.
              </p>

              <h3>
                What is the interior angle of a regular polygon with 20 sides?
              </h3>
              <p>
                For \(n = 20\): \[ A_{\text{int}} = \frac{(20 - 2)\times
                180^\circ}{20} = \frac{18\times 180^\circ}{20} =
                \frac{3240^\circ}{20} = 162^\circ. \] Each interior angle is
                162°, and each exterior angle is 18°.
              </p>
